{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527666"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:32:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:32:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14215"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14215"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.01,0.15,0.02,0.81]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6901"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102754"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6901"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14215"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85237"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4986"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5351"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11645"},{"type":"tags","id":"11648"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12733"},{"type":"tags","id":"12734"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15757"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32917"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39057"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102754"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old Aboriginal woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of persistent cough and fatigue. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. During the consultation, she mentions feeling hesitant about seeking medical care due to previous negative experiences in healthcare settings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs the healthcare provider, you want to ensure a culturally safe interaction.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following approaches is most likely to promote cultural safety in this healthcare interaction?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Focusing solely on the medical symptoms and avoiding discussion of cultural factors","Assuming all Aboriginal patients have similar health beliefs and practices","Telling the patient that you treat all patients exactly the same way regardless of their background","Immediately referring the patient to an Indigenous health worker without addressing her concerns","Acknowledging the impact of historical trauma on Indigenous health and wellbeing"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the most appropriate approach to promote cultural safety is \u003Cstrong\u003Eacknowledging the impact of historical trauma on Indigenous health and wellbeing\u003C/strong\u003E. This demonstrates an understanding of the broader context of Indigenous health and shows respect for the patient\u0027s experiences and background.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAssuming all Aboriginal patients have similar health beliefs and practices\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate and can lead to stereotyping. Indigenous peoples are diverse, with varied cultures, languages, and health beliefs. Each patient should be approached as an individual with their own unique experiences and perspectives.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFocusing solely on the medical symptoms and avoiding discussion of cultural factors\u003C/strong\u003E ignores the holistic nature of health in many Indigenous cultures. It also misses an opportunity to address the patient\u0027s expressed hesitation about seeking healthcare, which may be rooted in cultural or historical factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETelling the patient that you treat all patients exactly the same way regardless of their background\u003C/strong\u003E may seem fair on the surface, but it fails to recognise the unique historical, cultural, and social factors that influence Indigenous health. This \u0027colour-blind\u0027 approach can actually perpetuate inequities by ignoring important contextual factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediately referring the patient to an Indigenous health worker without addressing her concerns\u003C/strong\u003E could be seen as dismissive and may reinforce the patient\u0027s negative experiences with healthcare. While Indigenous health workers play a crucial role, it\u0027s important for all healthcare providers to be capable of providing culturally safe care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECultural safety goes beyond cultural awareness or sensitivity. It involves creating an environment free from racism and discrimination, where people feel safe receiving healthcare. This includes acknowledging the impact of colonisation, intergenerational trauma, and systemic racism on Indigenous health. By demonstrating an understanding of these factors, healthcare providers can build trust and create a more welcoming healthcare environment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProviding culturally safe care also involves continuous self-reflection, recognising one\u0027s own cultural biases, and being open to learning about Indigenous ways of knowing, being, and doing. It\u0027s about shifting the power dynamic in healthcare interactions to empower Indigenous patients and respect their right to quality, culturally appropriate healthcare.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cultural safety involves creating an environment free from racism and discrimination, where people feel safe receiving healthcare.","Acknowledging and respecting Indigenous ways of knowing, being, and doing is crucial for providing culturally safe care.","Continuous self-reflection and cultural awareness are essential for healthcare providers to deliver culturally safe care."],"references":["Australian Institute of Health and Welfare. (2023). Cultural safety in health care for Indigenous Australians: monitoring framework. Retrieved from https://www.aihw.gov.au/reports/indigenous-australians/cultural-safety-health-care-framework"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85237"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14215"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85237"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-15T12:51:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-15T14:44:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6901"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102754"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{